## Docker 

* Makes developing building and shipping softwares much easier.
* Docker solves the 'Compatibility issue'
* Let's say your application has components such as node mongodb redis etc. and each of these components have different libraries & dependencies. If you onboard a new developer on the project then setting the environment on his system will be a hassle. You will also face compatibility issues on deployment. eg. Different operating systems - different OS requirements.
* With docker you can run each of your components in a sepearte container with it's own dependencies and libraries all on the same virtual machine and the OS but within seperate environments or containers.
* We just have to build the docker configuration once and all the developers can get started with a single docker run command irrespective of their OS.

## Containers
* Containers are completely isolated environments, they have their own processes, services and their own network interfaces. 
* Containers are meant to run a specific task or process such as to host an instance of a web-server or application server or a database or simply to carry some kind of computation.
* The container only lives as long as the process inside it is alive.
* Unlike hypervisor docker is not meant to virtualize and run different operating systems and kernels on the same hardware. The main purpose of docker is to package and container as applications and to ship them and to run them as many times as you want.

## Container vs image
* An image is a package or a template just like a VM template and it is used to make one or more containers.
* Containers are running instances of images that are isolated and have their own environments and set of processes.

## Commands 
* docker run command is used to run a container from an image.
* docker ps command lists all running containers
* docker ps -a command lists all running/non-running containers
* docker stop <container-name or container-id> to stop a running container
* docker rm <container-name> to remove the container
* docker images to see a list of images
* docker rmi <image> to remove image. (ensure no container is using that image)
* docker pull <image> to download an image (and not run it immediately)
